---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Contact | latepaycalc.com';
const description = 'Contact latepaycalc.com for questions, corrections, or feedback on our late-payment invoice and final-paycheck penalty calculators.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Contact</h1>
  <p>Email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We're a small team, so email is the only channel we monitor &mdash; there's no live chat or phone line, and that's by design: late-payment questions, whether they're about an invoice or a paycheck, deserve a considered written answer, not a rushed one.</p>

  <h2>What we respond to</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Corrections to calculator math or citations.</strong> State commercial-interest rates, usury caps, and final-paycheck penalty statutes all change periodically. If a page cites a rate, formula, or statute that's out of date, tell us which page and what the correct figure is; we verify against the primary source before making any change.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors or unclear language in guides.</strong> If a sentence in a guide is ambiguous, contradicts itself, or is just hard to follow, we want to know &mdash; plain language is one of our core editorial standards.</li>
    <li><strong>Suggestions for new content.</strong> If you searched for a late-invoice or late-paycheck question and couldn't find it on the Site &mdash; a state we don't cover in enough depth, a scenario the calculator doesn't handle &mdash; let us know what you were trying to figure out.</li>
    <li><strong>Press and business inquiries.</strong> Journalists covering wage theft or commercial-payment issues, and businesses interested in advertising, can reach the same address.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to expect</h2>
  <p>We read every message. Corrections and editorial questions typically get a reply within a few business days. If a correction is verified, we update the affected page and note the date of the material change, consistent with our <a href="/editorial/">corrections policy</a>. We don't always reply to content suggestions individually, but we do track them for future guides.</p>

  <h2>What we don't respond to</h2>
  <p>We can't evaluate your specific invoice dispute or wage claim, tell you exactly what a court or state agency will award, or review a settlement or demand-letter number &mdash; that requires someone who has seen your contract, your pay records, or your state's actual filing. We also don't recommend specific attorneys, collection agencies, or payroll services, and we don't accept payment to feature or promote anyone on the Site. If you email us asking for case-specific advice, we'll point you back to this policy and to the guidance below.</p>

  <h2>Before you email</h2>
  <p>Many questions we get are already answered on the Site: check the <a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> for common questions on late-fee rates, taxability, and wage-claim recourse, or the <a href="/guides/">guides</a> &mdash; including <a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated/">how late-pay penalties are calculated</a>, <a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state/">final paycheck deadlines by state</a>, <a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late/">what to do if you've been paid late</a>, and <a href="/guides/common-late-pay-misconceptions/">common late-pay misconceptions</a>. If your question is about how the calculator arrived at a number, the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> walks through both formulas in detail, with worked examples.</p>

  <h2>If you need more than a calculator</h2>
  <p>We don't make referrals, but the right next step depends on which side of the Site you're using. If you're chasing an unpaid invoice, small claims court is often the fastest and cheapest option for amounts under your state's limit (commonly $5,000&ndash;$10,000, depending on the state), and doesn't usually require a lawyer; for larger commercial disputes, a business or collections attorney can send a formal demand letter and, if needed, pursue judgment. If you're owed final wages, the fastest free option is usually a wage claim filed directly with your state's labor department or labor commissioner's office &mdash; most process claims without requiring an attorney and can investigate, order payment, and assess penalties on your behalf. If the unpaid amount is large, the facts are disputed, or your employer is retaliating against you, a wage-and-hour employment attorney is worth a consultation; many take these cases on contingency because state law often awards attorney's fees on top of the wages and penalties. Either way, your state bar association's lawyer referral service can point you to an attorney who handles the relevant practice area if you'd rather start from a neutral source.</p>
</BaseLayout>
